 [ THE LEGACY ]

 Remember the mid-to-late 90s? The era when 3D graphics meant chunky 
 pixels and software rendering struggling on a Pentium? Then the 3dfx 
 Voodoo Graphics accelerator dropped in August 1996 and completely 
 changed the world. Suddenly, we had perspective-corrected texture 
 mapping, bilinear and trilinear filtering, polygonal-based Gouraud 
 shading, alpha blending, hardware depth-buffering, and high precision 
 sub-pixel correction. 
 
 If you were there, you remember booting into DOS to play those legendary 
 Glide-patched games. We traded chunky pixels for high-res roadkill in 
 Carmageddon, the Screamer series went blistering fast, and GLQuake blew 
 our minds with colored lighting and transparent water. This intro is a 
 tribute to that magical era of bare-metal DOS gaming and the hardware 
 that started the 3D accelerator revolution.

 [ THE CLAIM ]

 Maybe the very first 256b intro that targets the 3dfx Voodoo 1 card? 
 If you know anybody else who has done 3dfx in 256 bytes, please let me 
 know. I will not claim this is the first if it's already been done!

 [ TECHNICAL SPECS ]

 * 32-bit Flat / Unreal Mode entry
 * Bare-metal 3dfx Voodoo 1 PCI initialization (No Glide drivers!)
 * 3D CORDIC Rotations (Integer-only bitshifts)
 * Perfect 90-degree Lathe geometry generation
 * Lambert or Gouraud shading & Culling via direct face-normal math
 * Unified back-buffer Swap & Clear

 [ UNDER THE HOOD ]

 This code has been lurking for a year. On and off, size-optimizing the 
 memory setup and the Voodoo 1 initialization. It was a bitch to hack, 
 but now it's working. To squeeze this into 256 bytes, standard 
 conventions were thrown out the window. Here is the black magic:

 1. The 32-bit PMode / Unreal Mode Hack
 To access the Voodoo's MMIO and LFB at 0xD0000000, we need 32-bit flat 
 addressing. Standard Protected Mode setups waste bytes on GDT padding. 
 Instead, an overlapping 23-byte GDT is dynamically patched at runtime. 
 Flat 4GB selectors are loaded using a 3-byte stack trick (push 0x20, 
 pop ds, pop es). PMode is entered in a flash by shifting CS to find the 
 linear base, executing lgdt, and flipping the PE bit directly in CR0.

 2. Bare-Metal Voodoo 1 Initialization
 We completely bypass the glide2x.ovl API. To wake the card, the intro 
 manually hits the PCI configuration port 0xCF8. A clever 'jpe' loop 
 toggles the parity from 0x43 to 0xC3, enabling both INITENABLE and FIFO 
 in just a few bytes. 
 
 Once the PCI space is configured, writing to the FBIINIT0 register 
 triggers the Voodoo MMIO window. From there, FBZMODE is set to 
 0x00004601 (enabling Backbuffer, RGB+Z, and Clipping). Finally, scasd 
 and stosd instructions quickly step through memory to define the 
 clipping window constraints with maximum byte efficiency.

 3. 8-Bit Lathe Geometry & Lambert Culling
 To squeeze the 3D geometry into the binary, the octahedron is compressed 
 down to an 8-bit data array. The intro then utilizes a stack-based 
 90-degree lathe trick to duplicate and rotate the geometry on the fly, 
 completely eliminating the need to store the full model.
 The shading calculates face normals via simple imul instructions, pushing 
 the resulting delta values to the dRdX register to create a fake Gouraud 
 gradient across the polygons before hitting TRIANGLECMD.

 [ COMPATIBILITY ]

 I can't promise this will work on a real machine or any emulator other 
 than DOSbox-X. It probably won't. It's a bit tricky to get hold on a 
 working Voodoo 1 card these days.

